We recommended, and the Management agreed to direct:
The Municipal Accountant conduct a review of all dormant and long-outstanding accounts under the Due to NGAs ledger, and coordinate with concerned offices to determine appropriate actions such as liquidation, reversion, or closure of accounts;
The Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer immediately submit the liquidation reports for all completed projects and promptly return to the source agencies any unutilized balances from these projects;
The Municipal Accountant to prepare JEVs to record the necessary adjusting entries for unutilized funds and address discrepancies identified during the reconciliation process; and
The Municipal Accountant ensure the regular and timely submission of reports to the concerned source agencies on the status of fund utilization, liquidation, and remittance of unused balances.

We recommended, and the Management agreed to direct:
The Inventory Committee conduct semestral physical count of inventories and submit the result of the physical count using the RPCI to the Office of the Auditor not later than July 31 and January 31 of each year for the first and second semesters, respectively;
The GSO prepare and maintain stock cards and/or semi-expendable property cards for each supply/inventory and periodically reconcile the same with the accounting records and the result of the physical count;
Require the GSO to prepare monthly SSMI based on RIS from Requisitioning Unit/Office and submit the same to the Accounting Unit for the recording of appropriate expense account;
The Municipal Accountant prepare and maintain supply ledger cards and/or semi-expendable property ledger cards for each supply/inventory and periodically reconcile the same with the property records and the result of the physical count;
The Municipal Accountant observe the Perpetual Inventory Method by initially recording the purchases of supplies and materials as inventories and subsequently recognize the same as expenses upon issuance/distribution to Requisitioning Unit based on the monthly SSMI prepared by GSO; and
The Municipal Accountant provide appropriate disclosures in the notes to FS relative to the amount of inventory recognized as expenses during the year pursuant to Paragraph 47 of IPSAS 12.

We recommended, and the Management agreed to direct the following:
On the preparation of the BRS, the Municipal Accountant to:
Request for a monthly BS for all depository bank accounts. In the absence of BS or pending the approval of weAccess enrollment for Land Bank of the Philippines, request a copy of snapshots, duly certified by authorized bank representative;
Prepare the required BRS for all bank accounts so that reconciling items can be identified and submit the same, together with the supporting schedules to the audit team for verification;
Prepare the necessary journal entries to record the identified book reconciling items to reflect the corrected Cash in Bank account balances; and
The Municipal Treasurer provide the Municipal Accountant with official documents, such as but not limited to check issued, withdrawal slip and/or deposit slip, or other transfer documents, to prove the closure of the PNB 335-1174-00019 and PVB 0060-009015-001 accounts, account for the respective book balances and prepare the necessary adjustments, as warranted.

We recommended, and the Management agreed to ensure that:
Demand Letters were sent to concerned accountable officers and employees with outstanding cash advances for the immediate liquidation and/or settlement of their accounts. In case of non-liquidation and/or non-settlement, cause the withholding of salaries or any money claims due them;
Initiate immediate collection efforts for all outstanding receivables, particularly those that have been dormant for over ten years. This includes issuing demand letters to debtors, following up on overdue accounts, and exploring the possibility of legal action, if applicable;
Request for authority to write-off dormant accounts, following the guidelines, procedures and documentary requirements pursuant to COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016;
Refrain from granting additional cash advances to officers and employees who still have outstanding cash advances;
Review and reclassify accounts that are incorrectly recorded;
Cash advances must be disbursed by a designated SDO and not by personnel who are not officially part of the LGU;
Maintain detailed and accurate breakdowns of all receivables, particularly those with significant balances or negative amounts. This will ensure transparency and provide a clear basis for the valuation of receivables. For receivables that lack detailed information, further investigation be conducted to determine the origin and status of these amounts; and
Maintain a detailed report of collection efforts, including demand letters, follow-ups, and legal actions, for future reference and audit purposes.

The Municipal Treasurer immediately prepare a check to transfer the unspent and unobligated balance of DRRMF for CY 2023 from the GF to the TF;
The Municipal Accountant prepare the necessary adjusting journal entry to correct the liability account and recognize the transfer and receipt of DRRMF in the GF and TF books, respectively;
The Municipal Accountant trace the P7,790.00 difference to adjust and reflect the correct amount to be transferred and effect the necessary correcting entry; and
Moving forward, the Municipal Accountant ensure that the unexpended and unobligated balance of LDRRMF is transferred to the Trust Fund at year-end in conformity with Section 21 of RA 10121 and COA Circular No. 2012-002 and observe the proper recording thereof in the GF and TF books.

Direct the Municipal Treasurer to require the Collecting Officers delegated with the task of collecting taxes and other revenues of the LGU to apply with the Bureau of Treasury a bond sufficient to cover their cash accountability and monitor the compliance with the bonding requirement among collectors or AOs;
Strictly prohibit to designate Collecting Officers and employees with Job Order Status who are not bonded to collect; and
Review the plantilla position of the Treasury Office and deploy as collecting officers competent personnel/ staff, preferably computer literate, and those who possess high-degree of integrity and other core values, where trust and confidence can be reposed upon.

Establish a policy outlining the criteria, parameters, and processes in determining the amount of idle funds, procedures in identifying where to place the investments, its investment period, terms and conditions on the renewal and termination of investments, and other provisions deemed appropriate for investing idle funds, consistent with applicable laws and rules on the use of idle funds;
Ensure that investment plans and decisions using such idle funds are based on documented results of the analysis and review performed;
Direct concerned departments or offices to refrain from investing funds out of the Trust Fund and payable accounts where programmed projects are delayed or deferred as such practice is not in accordance with the intention of the law; and
Return the amount of trust liabilities to the trust fund book and the amount received from DBP as payable to Conequip Philippines, Inc.

